          "body": "Isaiah 24 opens with a word that demands arrest: *hinneh* — 'Behold.' What follows is not a threat but a vision already in motion: the LORD lays the earth waste, devastates it, distorts its surface, and scatters its inhabitants (24:1). Before the reader can ask 'which nation?', verse 2 answers: all of them, in every social category. Priest and people, master and servant, maid and mistress, buyer and seller, lender and borrower — the same fate falls on every economic and religious tier. This is the chapter's first great argument: divine judgment is no respecter of status. The religious office of the priest, the economic leverage of the lender, the social position of the mistress — none of these constitutes an exemption. Commentators like John Calvin noted that this leveling is itself a form of mercy in reverse: the same God who shows no partiality in grace shows no partiality in wrath. The guarantee of the devastation is the divine speech-act of 24:3: 'for the LORD has spoken this word.' What God has said is already done in the realm of decree; the historical unfolding is simply the word finding its object."
